n restructure their DNA if you spit on them", "url": "https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-facebook-plant-seeds-can-restructure-their-dna-if-you-spit-them"}, {"question": "Can plant seeds read and restructure their own DNA based on the DNA of a human through saliva?", "answer": "As the seed absorbs your saliva, it begins to read your DNA and structure its own genetic blueprint to be a superfood based on any defficiencies [sic] or requirements that your DNA is signalling."", "url": "https://www.boomlive.in/world/no-plant-seeds-cannot-restructure-their-own-dna-through-human-saliva-9462"}, {"question": "Can plant seeds read and restructure their own DNA based on human DNA signals from saliva?", "answer": "As the seed absorbs your saliva, it begins to read your DNA and structure its own genetic blueprint to be a superfood based on any defficiencies [sic] or requirements that your DNA is signalling.”", "url": "https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-facebook-plant-seeds-can-restructure-their-dna-if-you-spit-them"}, {"question": "Can plant seeds restructure their own DNA in response to nutrient deficiencies sensed from animal sources, such as human saliva?", "answer": ""Given the large amount of animal DNA that a plant encounters during its life cycle (e.g. earthworms, insects, birds) it would not be feasible for a plant to evolve in a manner that enabled it to recognise animal nutrient deficiencies and alter growth."", "url": "https://www.boomlive.in/world/no-plant-seeds-cannot-restructure-their-own-dna-through-human-saliva-9462"}, {"question": "Can plant seeds restructure their own DNA in response to the presence of animal DNA, such as that found in human saliva?", "answer": "“Given the large amount of animal DNA that a plant encounters during its life cycle (e.g. earthworms, insects, birds) it would not be feasible for a plant to evolve in a manner that enabled it to recognise animal nutrient deficiencies and alter growth.”", "url": "https://factcheck.afp.com/false-claim-circulates-facebook-plant-seeds-can-restructure-their-dna-if-you-spit-them"}, {"question": "What enzymes in human saliva are involved in breaking down starch in plant seeds?", "answer": "Specifically, enzymes called amylases aid in breaking starch into glucose with the help of water. The first amylases to act are those found in the saliva, encoded in the genome (the full set of heritable material of an organism) by one gene, called AMY1.", "url": "https://sitn.hms.harvard.edu/uncategorized/2014/starchy-dangers-in-human-evolution/"}], "pred_label": "Refuted", "llm_output": "<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

