{"claim_id": 16, "claim": "We actually saw revenues to the Treasury increase after we lowered taxes in 2017. Rest assured the Democrats do not want you to know that.", "evidence": [{"question": "Did the tax cuts in 2017 lead to an increase in Treasury revenues in the following year?", "answer": "While some TCJA supporters observe that nominal revenues were higher in fiscal year 2018 (which began Oct. 1, 2017) than in FY2017, that comparison does not address the question of the TCJA’s effects.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "Did the 2017 tax cuts lead to an increase in Treasury revenues?", "answer": "The most recent CBO projections estimate further decreases in corporate tax revenue. The TCJA also reduced income taxes for most Americans, which led to a decline in revenues relative to prior projections.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "According to the Congressional Budget Office, what were the projected corporate tax revenues for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 before the 2017 tax cuts?", "answer": "Several months before the TCJA was enacted, the Congressional Budget Office (CBO) projected that corporate tax revenues for fiscal years 2018 and 2019 would total $668 billion.", "url": "https://www.americanprogress.org/article/tcja-2-years-later-corporations-not-workers-big-winners/"}, {"question": "Did the actual amount of revenue collected by the US Treasury in FY2018 match the Congressional Budget Office's (CBO) projection made in January 2017?", "answer": "In fact, the actual amount of revenue collected in FY2018 was significantly lower than the Congressional Budget Office’s (CBO) projection of FY2018 revenue made in January 2017—before the tax cuts were signed into law in December 2017.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "Did the 2017 tax cut lead to an increase in tax revenue collected by the Treasury?", "answer": "The actual amount of tax revenue collected in FY2018 was significantly lower than the CBO’s projection made in January 2017—before the tax cut was signed into law.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "What was the change in payroll taxes after the tax cuts in 2017?", "answer": "In fact, payroll taxes fell only slightly—1.7%—from pre-TCJA projected values (Figure 2). This provides baseline credibility that reinforces the declines in other revenues.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "How did the actual tax revenue in FY2018 compare to the predicted tax revenue in FY2018 if the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act (TCJA) had not been passed?", "answer": "The most appropriate test of the revenue impact of the TCJA is to compare actual revenues in FY2018 with predicted revenues in FY2018 assuming Congress had not passed the legislation.", "url": "https://www.brookings.edu/articles/did-the-2017-tax-cut-the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-pay-for-itself/"}, {"question": "According to the CBO, what was the projected change in corporate tax revenue after the 2017 tax cuts?", "answer": "In the forecast published soon after the TCJA was enacted, however, the CBO projected $519 billion in corporate tax revenue over those two years—a $149 billion decrease.", "url": "https://www.americanprogress.org/article/tcja-2-years-later-corporations-not-workers-big-winners/"}, {"question": "Did corporate tax revenue decrease after the 2017 tax bill?", "answer": "Since the TCJA was enacted, corporate tax revenue has been down from its projected level by about one-third, even as pretax corporate profits have continued to rise toward historic highs.", "url": "https://www.americanprogress.org/article/tcja-2-years-later-corporations-not-workers-big-winners/"}, {"question": "How did the 2017 tax cuts affect federal revenue according to the evidence?", "answer": "- The individual income tax changes are scheduled to expire after December 31, 2025. If permanent, the income tax provisions would reduce federal revenue by $165 billion per year on a conventional basis, but when incorporating economic growth and feedback, on a dynamic basis, they would reduce federal revenue by $115 billion a year.", "url": "https://taxfoundation.org/research/all/federal/the-tax-cuts-and-jobs-act-simplified-the-tax-filing-process-for-millions-of-americans/"}], "pred_label": "Refuted", "llm_output": "<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

justification: The evidence shows that the revenues to the Treasury did not increase after the 2017 tax bill. 

