{"claim_id": 18, "claim": "A greater proportion of 16 year olds vote in elections in Scotland, Wales and Austria than 18 and 20 year olds.", "evidence": [{"question": "What is the comparison of the voting turnout rates between 16- to 17-year-olds and 18- to 20-year-olds in Scotland, Wales, and Austria?", "answer": "Overall, the level of turnout is generally higher among 16- to 17-year-olds (compared to 18- to 20-year-olds) and similar to the electorate’s average (and here in particular amongst the 16-year-olds), as evidenced by official records from electoral lists.", "url": "https://www.democraticaudit.com/2020/02/26/what-happens-when-the-voting-age-is-lowered-to-16-a-decade-of-evidence-from-austria/"}, {"question": "In Austria, what is the turnout rate of 16 and 17-year-olds to elections?", "answer": "This article examines turnout of young voters aged 16 to 17 in Austria, the first European country that lowered the general voting age to 16.", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27226806/"}, {"question": "In which countries have 16- and 17-year-olds been allowed to vote in elections?", "answer": "This literature is limited given the few cases in which 16- to 17-year-olds have been able to vote. Austria is the only Western country that has lowered the voting age to 16 for all elections, since 2007.Footnote 1 Alternatively, in Norway, 16- and 17-year-olds were allowed to vote in ‘trial elections’ in 20 municipalities in 2011; in Germany, since the 1990s, a few states have allowed 16- to 17-year-olds to vote in municipal or state elections; and in Scotland, 16- and 17-year-olds were allowed to vote in the 2014 independence referendum.", "url": "https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/canadian-journal-of-political-science-revue-canadienne-de-science-politique/article/lowering-the-voting-age-to-16-a-comparative-study-on-the-political-competence-and-engagement-of-underage-and-adult-youth/0E864E593EF252197F913616F97CE75D"}, {"question": "In Scotland, what percentage of 16 and 17-year-olds who registered to vote in the 2014 independence referendum actually turned out to vote compared to the 18-24-year-olds?", "answer": "They can pick up the voting habit by accompanying their parents to polling stations. In Scotland, where 16- and 17-year-olds were eligible to vote in the independence referendum in 2014, an impressive three-quarters of those who registered turned out on the day, compared with 54% of 18- to 24-year-olds.", "url": "https://www.economist.com/leaders/2017/02/04/why-the-voting-age-should-be-lowered-to-16"}, {"question": "In comparison to 18 and 20-year-olds, what is the general level of turnout among 16- to 17-year-old voters?", "answer": "among adolescent voters aged 16–17. Overall, the level of turnout is generally higher among 16- to 17-year-olds", "url": "http://eprints.lse.ac.uk/107833/2/dit_com_2020_02_26_what_happens_when_the_voting_age_is_lowered_to_16.pdf"}, {"question": "How do the voting turnout rates of 16-year-olds compare to those of 18 and 20-year-olds in Scotland, Wales, and Austria?", "answer": "In 2007 Austria became the only rich country where 16-year-olds could vote in all elections. Encouragingly, turnout rates for under-18s are markedly higher than for 19- to 25-year-olds.", "url": "https://www.economist.com/leaders/2017/02/04/why-the-voting-age-should-be-lowered-to-16"}, {"question": "In Austria, what is the reported turnout rate of 16 and 17-year-olds at the 2013 general election?", "answer": "At the next general election in 2013 though, the Austrian National Election Study (AUTNES) confirmed that first-time voters went to the polls far less than older voters.7 The reported turnout of the 16-to-17-year olds was 63%, which is significantly lower than the reported general turnout of 80%.", "url": "https://www.realinstitutoelcano.org/en/analyses/voting-at-16-in-austria-a-possible-model-for-the-eu/"}, {"question": "What is the voting turnout level of 16- and 17-year-olds in Scotland, Wales, and Austria compared to the total electorate?", "answer": "In turn, the turnout level of 16- and 17-year-olds even approaches that of the total electorate. These findings generally corroborate earlier evidence reported by Zeglovits and Aichholzer.", "url": "https://www.democraticaudit.com/2020/02/26/what-happens-when-the-voting-age-is-lowered-to-16-a-decade-of-evidence-from-austria/"}, {"question": "What is the range of the difference in turnout rates between 16- and 17-year-olds and 18- to 20-year-olds in Scotland, Wales, and Austria?", "answer": "The gap in the level of turnout between this group of adolescents and older first-time voters (18- to 20-year-olds) ranges between +2.3% and +10.0%, meaning that 16- and 17-year-olds are more likely to turn out to vote than older first-time voters.", "url": "https://www.democraticaudit.com/2020/02/26/what-happens-when-the-voting-age-is-lowered-to-16-a-decade-of-evidence-from-austria/"}, {"question": "What do studies suggest about the voting turnout of 16 and 17-year-olds compared to 18 to 21-year-olds?", "answer": "These latter studies, which show a higher turnout among 16- and 17-year-olds than 18- to 21-year-olds, are indicative of a larger point: 18 is a terrible age to vote.", "url": "https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2016/11/7/13347080/voting-age-election-16"}], "pred_label": "Supported", "llm_output": "<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

