chanism similar to febrile seizures4,9.", "url": "https://www.scielo.br/j/anp/a/9rY8d96bFkHcD5hvsm9Dj6p/"}, {"question": "Is warm water a trigger for seizures in people with epilepsy?", "answer": "Hot water epilepsy has been previously studied and reported, occurring mainly in India1,2,3. Both partial and generalized tonic-clonic seizures related to hot water bathing have been described as temperature-related, often triggered by temperatures ranging from 40 to 50ºC1-3.", "url": "https://www.scielo.br/j/anp/a/9rY8d96bFkHcD5hvsm9Dj6p/"}, {"question": "Does the evidence suggest that warm water has a therapeutic effect on epilepsy?", "answer": "The authors considerate that in patients with refractory seizures, bathing epilepsy should be sought, and that seizures susceptibility might reflect focal phenomena in a generalized excitable cortex (Guilhoto LMFF, Degenszajn J. J Epilepsy Clin Neurophysiol 2004;10(Suppl 1):8.", "url": "https://www.scielo.br/j/anp/a/9rY8d96bFkHcD5hvsm9Dj6p/"}, {"question": "Is warm water a treatment for epilepsy?", "answer": "The major findings in bathing epilepsy are that it has a male preponderance with ratios higher than 70% for men3,5, can be self-induced, is known as benign and self-limited, often performed for pleasure, has complex triggering factors, and shows temporally-related abnormalities in the EEG tracings1,5.", "url": "https://www.scielo.br/j/anp/a/9rY8d96bFkHcD5hvsm9Dj6p/"}, {"question": "Is warm water effective in treating epilepsy?", "answer": "Hot water epilepsy: seizure type, water temperature, EEG findings and treatment", "url": "https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20220445/"}], "pred_label": "Refuted", "llm_output": "<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

