{"claim_id": 158, "claim": "With African Americans, Trump is doing very well. They had the best employment numbers they’ve ever had. ... They were making more money than they ever made.", "evidence": [{"question": "What was the unemployment rate for Black Americans in January 1972?", "answer": "Trump is right that African-American unemployment hit a record low in December. The unemployment rate for black Americans is currently 6.8 percent, the lowest level recorded since the government started keeping track in January 1972.", "url": "https://www.npr.org/2018/01/08/576552028/fact-check-trump-touts-low-unemployment-rates-for-african-americans-hispanics"}, {"question": "Did the median income of African American households increase during Trump's administration compared to the previous year?", "answer": "African Americans also had higher income prior to the Trump administration. A black household earned median income of $40,258 in 2017, the latest data available.", "url": "https://apnews.com/article/f78f4205f474482db8bb8fa7a5ebfa27"}, {"question": "Did the employment rate for African Americans increase during Trump's administration, and did their median household income also see a significant increase?", "answer": "High employment under Trump led to minorities experiencing the largest income gains. Real median income grew by 7.9% for Blacks in 2019.", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/11/01/donald-trump-african-american-black-economic-progress-vote-column/6081310002/"}, {"question": "Did the unemployment rate for African Americans reach a record low during the Trump administration?", "answer": "It’s true that black unemployment did reach a record low during the Trump administration: 5.9 percent in May 2018.", "url": "https://apnews.com/article/f78f4205f474482db8bb8fa7a5ebfa27"}, {"question": "Did the poverty rate among African Americans decrease in 2019 to a record low under Trump's administration?", "answer": "Income gains for Blacks translated into real economic mobility. Not only did the poverty rate for Blacks fall to an all time record low in 2019, but it also dipped below 20% for the first time.", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/11/01/donald-trump-african-american-black-economic-progress-vote-column/6081310002/"}, {"question": "Did the employment rate for African Americans increase during Trump's administration, and if so, how quickly did it recover from the recession high of 16.8% in March 2010?", "answer": "Black employment increased by 1.3 million from April to September. It took years for the Black unemployment rate to fall from a recession high of 16.8% in March 2010 back down to 12%, whereas it only took a handful of months during the pandemic, likely because the economy is so resilient.", "url": "https://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2020/11/01/donald-trump-african-american-black-economic-progress-vote-column/6081310002/"}, {"question": "Did the economic policies of the Trump administration lead to a reduction in the income and employment gaps between African Americans and whites?", "answer": "Between 1996 and 2000, for example, as the economy neared full employment, the income and employment gaps between blacks and whites shrank.42 When the Great Recession hit in 2007-09, blacks were more negatively affected and struggled for a longer period of time to return to their prerecession wages and employment rates.43 In addition, black families have been disproportionately affected by the decline in union density.", "url": "https://www.americanprogress.org/article/systematic-inequality/"}, {"question": "Did the unemployment rate for African Americans decrease during the period from 1993 to 2000?", "answer": "Unemployment dropped from more than 7 percent in 1993 to just 4.0 percent in November 2000. Unemployment for African Americans and Hispanics fell to the lowest rates on record, and the rate for women is the lowest in more than 40 years.", "url": "https://clintonwhitehouse5.archives.gov/WH/Accomplishments/eightyears-01.html"}, {"question": "Did the Trump administration's policies lead to higher wage growth for historically disadvantaged groups, including African Americans?", "answer": "The Trump Administration’s policies are not only leading to more jobs but also to higher pay. While nominal wage growth for all private-sector workers has been at or above 3 percent for a year and a half, wage growth for many historically-disadvantaged groups is now higher than wage growth for more historically-advantaged groups—reversing trends observed over the Obama Administration’s expansion period, as shown in the figure below.", "url": "https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/articles/the-trump-economy-benefits-historically-disadvantaged-americans/"}, {"question": "What happened to the poverty rates for African Americans and Hispanic Americans during the first two years of the Trump Administration?", "answer": "Over the first two years of the Trump Administration, the number of people living in poverty decreased by about 2.5 million—including nearly 1 million children of single mothers—and the poverty rates for African Americans and Hispanic Americans are at record lows.", "url": "https://trumpwhitehouse.archives.gov/articles/the-trump-economy-benefits-historically-disadvantaged-americans/"}], "pred_label": "Supported", "llm_output": "<|start_header_id|>assistant<|end_header_id|>

